recordings.type: call, unusual rhythm to part of the call
recordings.rmk: The phoebe was low in brush near the edge of a tidal river.  It is a fairly common wintering species in this location.  The recording was made with a Sound Devices 722 and a Sennheiser ME67 shotgun microphone.  There is an unusual twist to the call which is rare to my ears. It occurs shortly after the first and loudest vocalization The recording itself was boosted about 10dB gain and some human interference was eliminated as well as some more of the nuthatch calls to avoid confusion.  Consequently the intervals between vocalizations has been altered in spots.

recordings.rmk:
Flying agitatedly among several perches in the Tupelo Gum trees. Brief agonistic encounters with a second EAPH (heard in the background). Aggression calls at 0:01 and 0:44.  Distance from microphone variable 3 to 5 meters. 

#Habitat#
Boardwalk through Cypress/Tupelo Gum swamp. Initially thick Tupelo Gum stand and then opens up into a broad open, grassy swamp with some isolated trees.  

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 700 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Malibu Legacy Park, Los Angeles County, California
recordings.rmk:
Natural vocalizations by an eastern phoebe.  Malibu legacy park is an open area with scattered bushes and native grasses that surround a small wetland.  The bird was about 10 meters from me when it was vocalizing.

Eastern phoebe is a rare bird at this location.  Entered into Xeno-Canto primarily for documentation.

Photographed extensively.

The eastern phoebe often chased a black phoebe while we watched.  Both species are audible on the recording. 

Abundant noise from vehicles on Pacific Coast Highway is also audible.

Equipment: Olympus LS-10S equipped with a Sennheiser MKE-400.
File modifications: cropped at both ends.

recordings.loc: Montréal, Communauté-Urbaine-de-Montréal, Québec
recordings.rmk:
The record was filtered to reduce noise at low frequency (water stream from big hose) and noise reduction was  applied lightly from an audio program (Audacity).This is a unique recording of this bird.
This bird is adult and  probably she is nesting. In this park with  many big trees and bush close to a pond, she was seen and heard on a branch, 15 meters above microphone when she reacted of Cooper Hawk fly by her nest in an old house roof. So her typical song was repeated at intervals of 1.5 s. and the second song was a high tonality chip at 1 s. A photograph is taken to confirm identity. This was recorded half an hour before sunset, may 12th 2016.   Daylight was good and no wind and no rain or humidity.
